body:
`Port.try_recv()` returns `None` if the respective `Chan` has been closed. If you call it again, it fails. I expect it to continue to return `None`.
## Minimal test case

``` rust
fn main() {
    let (port, chan) = stream();
    do spawn {
        chan.send(42i);
    }
    assert_eq!(port.try_recv(), Some(42i));
    assert_eq!(port.try_recv(), None);
    println("Got this far, as expected, but alas—");
    assert_eq!(port.try_recv(), None);
    println("No further :-(");
}
```
## Run output

```
Got this far, as expected, but alas—
rust: task failed at 'option::unwrap none', /home/chris/vc/rust/src/libstd/option.rs:283
rust: domain main @0x23cd1b0 root task failed
```
## Cause

[`src/libstd/comm.rs`, lines 679-687](https://github.com/mozilla/rust/blob/master/src/libstd/comm.rs#L679..L687):

``` rust
                let self_endp = transmute_mut(&self.endp);
                let endp = replace(self_endp, None);
                match try_recv(endp.unwrap()) {
                    Some(streamp::data(x, endp)) => {
                        *self_endp = Some(endp);
                        Some(x)
                    }
                    None => None
                }
```

It can be seen there that `self.endp` is left as `None` on the first call after the chan is closed, and so `endp` will be `None` on the second such call, which naturally causes `endp.unwrap()` to fail.

Unfortunately, it looks uncomfortably like it's intentional. I certainly do not want it to be intentional—or if it must be, provide a better failure than "option::unwrap none".
